# delete-llm.word, a being deletes one of its connections from its OWN being (llm-assigner/ops.js
# delete-llm DO op). PURE-COMPOSITION / delegation: the whole effect is ONE entailed deed,
# `do delete-llm-connection` on the caller's own being, carrying { connectionId }. That seed op is
# itself WORD-SOLE (store/words/llm-connection), so this is words all the way down, the unset
# (set-being value:null at qualities.llmConnections.<id>) folds through the entailed deed's path.
#
# WORD-SOLE (handler-less, Tabor's no-mirror law): this `.word` is the ONLY path. do.js's
# runOpWordToStore runs it through runWordToStore (runAsStore), so the entailed deed seals its OWN
# moment on the caller's reel. The op lays NO fact of its own, the entailed do:delete-llm-connection
# deed IS the record. No host read: a delegator reads nothing of the floor.
#
# The bridge binds `caller` (the actor's beingId, the being the connection is removed from) and
# the op `params` (connectionId), spread top-level too.

When a being deletes a connection of its own:
  If no caller, refuse with "delete-llm requires an authenticated being." as unauthorized.
  do delete-llm-connection on the being $caller with { connectionId: $params.connectionId } as removed.
  Return removed: $removed.
